Rating: 3
This will be my enthusiastic third winter for making this soup, which has enthralled family and guests since I first delightedly found it. Unless the entire recipe will be eaten immediately, it's best to cook the orzo in a separate pot (using some of the chicken broth, if desired, or water, if you prefer to dump the starch from the pasta, as I do, rather than adding it to the soup, which is going to be thin anyway) and add it only to the amount of soup that will be served (or to each soup plate). Otherwise the orzo (or any other small pasta) will turn to mush as it sits. Turkey broth would be a fine substitute for chicken broth here, and after Thanksgiving, a few stray strands of turkey would not go amiss to make the soup even heartier. It's really a meal as it is, and a very fine lunch on a cold day. Articles have appeared recently that encourage the millions of us who don't qualify for flu shots to nourish ourselves well to boost our immune systems. To that end, I plan to make and freeze a double batch of this soup (to use the whole head of escarole) to heat when I get the flu and this kind of hot, nourishing mildness is the only food that appeals. It's a good way to get a little protein down, too, when one is feeling fragile. Reviewers who say they like to brown the meatballs before adding them to the pot are harking back to this recipe's apparent predecessor (still available on Epicurious), a 1995 Gourmet recipe for Escarole Soup with Turkey Meatballs. I have not found any problem with skipping that messy, caloric step. I think the 2003 version is an improvement in other ways as well. Unlike one or more reviewers who question the use of carrots, I like them. I think they provide taste interest and a necessary dash of color.

